diff:1194842385:1194842343:=1c1%0a%3c Sometimes at night during goodnight circle we would sing this song.  It's always sad, but it's even sadder when we sing it on the last few nights of camp.   Sometimes on these days I thought I should be crying but I wouldn't be, so I would think about the song.%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a---%0a> Sometimes at night when we sign at goodnight circle we sing this song.  It's always sad, but it's even sadder when we sing it on the last few nights of camp.   Sometimes on these days I thought I should be crying but I wouldn't be, so I would think about the song so that my friends wouldn't think I was heartless.%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
host:1194842385=134.173.192.122
author:1194842343=stumpy
diff:1194842343:1194771155:=1c1%0a%3c Sometimes at night when we sign at goodnight circle we sing this song.  It's always sad, but it's even sadder when we sing it on the last few nights of camp.   Sometimes on these days I thought I should be crying but I wouldn't be, so I would think about the song so that my friends wouldn't think I was heartless.%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a---%0a> Every night at my camp we all join hands (crossing right arm over left) and we sing a few songs before we go to bed.  The last two songs are always the same.  When I first starting going to camp at age seven, we sang songs about the moon and other lighthearted topics.  As I got older, the songs got deeper and darker.  I learned this song when I was an intermediate (approximately 11 years old).  Learning this song was a sort off rite of passage at my camp--the mark of growing up, as cheesy as it sounds.%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
host:1194842343=134.173.192.122
author:1194771155=stumpy
diff:1194771155:1194630187:=1c1%0a%3c Every night at my camp we all join hands (crossing right arm over left) and we sing a few songs before we go to bed.  The last two songs are always the same.  When I first starting going to camp at age seven, we sang songs about the moon and other lighthearted topics.  As I got older, the songs got deeper and darker.  I learned this song when I was an intermediate (approximately 11 years old).  Learning this song was a sort off rite of passage at my camp--the mark of growing up, as cheesy as it sounds.%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a---%0a> Every night at my camp we all join hands (crossing right arm over left) and we sing a few songs before we go to bed.  The last two songs are always the same.  When I first starting going to camp at age seven, we sang songs about the moon and other lighthearted topics.  As I got older, the songs got deeper and darker.  I learned this song when I was an intermediate (appproximately 11 years old).  I remembered feeling older, knowing that learning this song was a privilege given to tthe older girls.%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
